HTML customization (phased rollout) — Koy's answer to MySpace-era full-HTML editing, but architected for safety and performance. Three phases:
Phase A (ships with Sprint 5 Editor Seed): Token-based theming + curated CSS classes. Users pick CSS variable values (`--accent-color`, `--font-display`) and apply named effects ("glitter overlay," "TV scan-lines," "VHS distortion"). Limited but mobile-safe and performant.
Phase B (Sprint 10+): Sandboxed CSS-only customization for power users. "Custom CSS" tab in advanced editor settings. Strict allow-list of properties (no `position: fixed`, no animations longer than X seconds, no external resource loading). Sanitized through CSS parser before save. CSS-only, no JavaScript ever.
Phase C (post-launch, post-stability): Sandboxed HTML iframe blocks for power users wanting MySpace-level freedom. Special "Code Block" type that renders user-written HTML/CSS in an isolated iframe (browser sandbox prevents escape). Rate-limited. Likely gated to premium tier.
What we will NEVER ship: unrestricted HTML/JS injection into user pages. Section 18 Protection 5 forbids it (security/performance risk), Protection 7 makes it unnecessary (soft guardrails achieve the same expressive feeling without consequences). MySpace's mistake was making this freedom default; we make it gated, sandboxed, and earned.
