18. THE SEVEN PROTECTIONS — KOY'S MYSPACE-AWARE PRINCIPLES
Meta-principle: "Constrained systems, unconstrained feeling."
Allow emotional chaos. Prevent technical chaos. Users should feel unlimited freedom while invisible systems quietly maintain coherence underneath. The editor should feel chaotic, playful, alive. The output must be readable and responsive. Different optimization targets for different surfaces of the same product.
This meta-principle governs how all seven protections below get applied. We don't ban chaos, we shape it. We don't enforce taste, we curate amplification. We don't restrict creation, we discipline mechanics.
MySpace, Tumblr, AIM, Winamp, Discord, Roblox — each got pieces of this right and pieces wrong. Koy's discipline is to absorb all the lessons without becoming sterile in the process. The seven protections below are constitutional — they get baked into the sprint that introduces the relevant feature, not retrofitted later.
Protection 1: Creator Visibility
The risk: Algorithm rewards already-popular creators. New creators stay invisible. Discovery becomes a popularity contest where the same accounts win every week. Late-period MySpace homepage feed.
The principle: Every creator deserves a fair shot at being seen. Visibility is not a winner-take-all distribution.
Owned by:
Sprint 8 (Discovery feeds) — algorithm spec MUST include:
"Rising Creators" feed surface separate from "Trending" — surfaces accounts with strong recent engagement velocity, not absolute follower counts
Decay function on creator promotion — same creator can't dominate "Featured" slots more than once per N weeks
"New on Koy" feed — surfaces accounts under 30 days old with non-zero engagement
Personalized feeds weight novelty, not just popularity
Sprint 9 (Contests) — featured-creator slots include explicit reservations for first-time winners
Ongoing: "Follow" mechanism (currently not specced) so users can subscribe to specific creators and see their new pages independent of feed algorithms. Add to Sprint 8 scope.
Protection 2: Discovery Fairness
The risk: Viral content begets more viral content. Diversity collapses. Every user's feed looks the same. Algorithm becomes a centralized cultural gatekeeper.
The principle: Discovery surfaces represent the diversity of the platform, not the loudest signals.
Owned by:
Sprint 8 (Discovery feeds) — algorithm spec MUST include:
Diversity injection: every feed reserves N% of slots for accounts the user hasn't seen before
Anti-pile-on damping: viral signals get sub-linear weighting (popular gets popular slower than naive trending math)
Persona/category awareness: a working mom's feed defaults to relevant content, not the trader pages dominating overall trending
Regional/timezone fairness: at scale, ensure global users aren't drowned out by US-peak-hours signals
Documentation requirement: When Sprint 8 ships, publish a "How discovery works" page. Transparency is fairness infrastructure. Hidden algorithms erode trust.
Appeals process: When shadow-banning or moderation actions exist, document the appeals path before the action is allowed. (Add to Sprint 6 scope.)
Protection 3: Aesthetic Quality
The risk: Open marketplace floods with low-effort listings. Buyers can't tell good from bad. Quality creators leave. Marketplace becomes a graveyard.
The principle: Open supply with curated quality signals. Anyone can sell, but quality is rewarded in discovery, not gatekept at creation. We never tell a creator "your work isn't good enough to exist." We tell discovery surfaces "amplify the work that demonstrates craft."
Important framing (per controlled-freedom meta-principle): Aesthetic quality protection does NOT mean blocking ugly pages. Some users will make pages we'd never feature. That's their right and Koy's authenticity. Quality protection means the featured slots, trending feeds, and homepage placements go to work that meets standards — chaos still exists, it just doesn't get amplified above the work that doesn't deserve to drown it out.
Owned by:
Sprint 6 (Marketplace v1) — must ship with:
Floor pricing ($8.99) — already specced, do not lower
Two-tier pricing (general vs. featured) so quality can command premium
Featured-creator badges visible on listings
"Completeness check" before a listing can publish — minimum block count, minimum customization (not a quality judgment, just confirms the listing is meaningfully different from a default template)
Refund/dispute handling that protects buyers from blatantly low-effort listings
Sprint 9 (Contests) — feed quality continuously via contest winners → featured slots
Architectural rule: Skeleton-only marketplace transfers (already locked) prevent low-effort "copy and re-list" exploitation
Editor Self-Expression Seed (Sprint 5) — prevents generic platform look at the foundation level
Don't fear ugly. After-MySpace founders over-correct toward sterile. Koy must not remove personality in pursuit of "good design." The goal is to amplify well-crafted chaos, not eliminate chaos.
Protection 4: Anti-Spam Systems
The risk: Bots, fake accounts, comment spam, fake engagement, marketplace abuse. Most under-architected of the four. Will hit Koy on day one of public launch.
The principle: Trust is earned, not granted. Systems assume abuse and design against it.
Owned by:
Pre-launch (Section 15 checklist):
Email verification ON
Comment "report" button + manual review queue
Comment word blocklist
Rate limit on user_events writes
Rate limit on comments (5/user/min)
Sprint 6 (Marketplace v1) — must add:
Rate limit on marketplace listings (max N/day per user)
Bot detection on signup (CAPTCHA or similar at scale)
Cross-account abuse detection (one IP, many accounts gaming the system)
Fake-engagement detection (purchases from accounts with no other activity, like-spam patterns)
Sprint 8 (Discovery feeds) — must add:
Engagement-quality signals (a "use" from a 1-day-old account weighs less than from a 6-month account)
Network-clustering detection (group of accounts liking only each other)
Sprint 9 (Contests) — must add:
Rate limit on contest submissions
Submission quality minimum (same completeness check as marketplace)
Anti-collusion rules (can't have multiple accounts submitting variants of the same design)
Protection 5: Modern UX Discipline
The risk: Customization comes at the cost of performance. MySpace pages took 30+ seconds to load on dial-up; even on broadband, autoplay music + animated GIFs + custom CSS + embedded widgets crashed browsers. The customization that gave MySpace its identity also killed it. Koy's current architecture (single-file React, no caching, no lazy-load, image-heavy public pages with no CDN) starts producing the same problem at scale.
The principle: Customization without compromise. Every feature ships fast, responsive, mobile-friendly, and intuitive — or it doesn't ship.
The acceptance floor (every sprint, not just one):
Fast: Public pages load under 2 seconds on 4G. Editor opens under 1 second.
Responsive: Every interaction responds in under 200ms. Save/upload feedback under 500ms.
Mobile-friendly: Every feature works mobile-first. If it can't ship cleanly on iPhone, it doesn't ship.
Intuitive: New user can complete the core action (create a page, upload an image, share their URL) without instructions. Test with real humans, not assumptions.
Owned by:
Every sprint from now forward. Not a one-time sprint, an ongoing rule applied to every PR.
Sprint 2.5 (Design Pass) — first formal application: redesign for performance and intuitiveness, not just aesthetics
Sprint 4 (Package Architecture) — state management refactor with `useAppState()` hook addresses the "everything re-renders" performance issue
Sprint 6 or 7 (Scale Prep, parallel track) — file split refactor, React Query caching, CDN in front of Supabase Storage, image transcoding. Doesn't ship before launch but must ship before crossing 10k users.
Pre-launch checklist (Section 15) — performance audit before announcing publicly
Architectural rules going forward:
No new dependency adds 50KB+ to bundle without justification
Every public page must be code-split from editor (separate chunks)
Every list/feed must paginate, never render all-at-once
Every image upload must be width-constrained on render (don't ship full-res to mobile)
Every embed (YouTube, Spotify, etc.) must lazy-load
Every animation must respect `prefers-reduced-motion`
Protection 6: Policy Stability
The risk: Tumblr destroyed user trust overnight in 2018 with the NSFW ban. Users had built communities, identities, archives — and the platform reversed core policy with weeks of notice. Trust that took a decade to build evaporated in days. Discord faces similar pressure on community policies. App stores force these reversals on platforms regularly.
The principle: Major user-facing policies (content allowed, monetization rules, visibility defaults, marketplace fees) don't reverse without long deprecation windows and clear communication. We earn trust by being predictable.
Locked-in commitments (constitutional):
Public-with-link visibility default doesn't reverse to private-by-default. Pages users created with public-share expectations stay public-shareable.
NSFW deferred 12+ months minimum (already in Section 9). If we ever flip this either direction (allow then ban, or ban then allow), we communicate 6 months in advance.
User content ownership. Anything a user creates on Koy belongs to them. We don't retroactively claim rights, train commercial models on their work without consent, or repurpose their content for marketing without explicit opt-in.
Marketplace fee strategy (deferred, not constitutionally locked):
Khalid's call: rate-setting authority belongs to founder, not architectural lock. Pricing decisions deferred until post-launch when real revenue and creator behavior provide signal. Roblox lesson stands: high take rates damage creator trust. Anchor: aim for the 10–20% range historically associated with creator-friendly platforms (Etsy, Gumroad). Above 20% raises trust questions; above 30% replicates Roblox's creator revolts.
Procedural protection that IS locked (per Tumblr lesson): any fee change announced post-launch must come with 6 months notice and direct creator communication, not silently in a TOS update. Increases above 20% require existing creator opt-out provision (they retain old rate on existing listings). This protects Koy's trust signal even while leaving rate flexibility intact.
Owned by:
Section 14 (What Not To Do) — these commitments belong on the "never break this" list
Pre-launch (Section 15) — Privacy Policy and Terms of Service must explicitly codify the locked-in commitments above. Don't write generic ToS templates that allow reversal.
Every sprint: if a future sprint spec proposes changing any of the above, reject it. If circumstances genuinely change (legal, business, technical), the response is "long deprecation + communication," not "ship the change quietly."
Protection 7: Soft Guardrails Philosophy
The risk: Founders over-correct after MySpace toward hard restrictions. They limit customization, force clean templates, ban features users want. The cure becomes the disease. Sterilization kills emotional engagement.
The principle: Use invisible guidance instead of visible restrictions. The system enforces coherence; the user experiences freedom.
Architectural patterns required (every sprint):
Smart contrast correction. When a user picks a dark background, text auto-flips to readable color. Already implemented in Sprint 2 calendar cells (color picker auto-contrast). Apply pattern everywhere user-customized colors meet text.
Performance caps via degradation, not prohibition. "Too many GIFs" → system serves smaller versions / lazy-loads aggressively / compresses on upload. Never "GIFs not allowed."
Snap systems for free-form positioning. Users drag freely, but invisible alignment helps things look intentional. Already partially implemented in calendar freeform mode. Extend to block placement on canvas.
Layer warnings, not blocks. "You have 18 freeform elements in this cell, max is 20" — informational, lets the user decide. Never silent failure or hard block.
Aesthetic Lanes. Templates and packages provide subcultural defaults (Y2K, terminal, scrapbook, soft pastel, brutalist, trader-core, etc.) so users start in a coherent aesthetic and can customize from there. Chaos becomes organized culture, not visual soup. Drives package strategy in Sprint 5+.
Editor experience and output experience optimize differently. The editor can feel chaotic, playful, full of options and animation. The published page must be performant and readable. Don't apply editor-side complexity penalties to output-side performance.
Owned by:
Every sprint from now forward. This is a UX design philosophy that informs every feature build, same as Protection 5.
Sprint 2.5 (Design Pass) — first formal application: identify where hard restrictions exist that should be soft guardrails instead. Refactor where appropriate (cosmetic-only).
Architect's role: When writing future specs, default to soft guardrails. If a spec calls for a hard block (e.g., "users can't do X"), justify why a soft guardrail (e.g., "users get warned about X but can override") doesn't work for that case.
How these get enforced
When writing any future sprint spec, the architect must check this section and confirm which protections that sprint owns. Not "add to backlog" — actually written into the sprint's acceptance criteria. Section 18 is the constitutional constraint on Sprint specs from Sprint 6 onward.
Special cases:
Protection 5 (Modern UX Discipline): every sprint owns this. Every PR must demonstrate fast/responsive/mobile-friendly/intuitive on Khalid's phone before merge.
Protection 6 (Policy Stability): every sprint must verify it doesn't propose reversing a locked-in commitment.
Protection 7 (Soft Guardrails): every sprint defaults to soft guardrails over hard restrictions. Hard blocks require explicit architect justification.
The controlled-freedom test: before any feature ships, ask:
Does this give the user a feeling of expressive freedom? (Emotional chaos allowed.)
Does this maintain technical coherence — performance, readability, mobile-friendly? (Technical chaos prevented.)
If forced to choose between the two for this feature, which side falls? (Bias toward emotional freedom; engineer harder on the technical side.)
If a future Claude or developer is unclear whether a protection applies to their work, the rule is: the sprint that introduces the feature owns the protection for that feature. If marketplace ships without anti-spam rate limits, that's a violation. If discovery feeds ship without diversity injection, that's a violation. If any feature ships slow or unintuitive, that's a violation. If a sprint proposes raising the marketplace fee above 15%, that's a violation. If a feature ships with hard restrictions where soft guardrails would have worked, that's a violation.
